Title:
Hiding Malicious Code with Module Stomping

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post describes “module stomping,” a Windows in-memory code injection technique where an attacker overwrites the executable sections of a legitimately loaded DLL/module with malicious payload code.  
- The goal is to evade detections that focus on suspicious memory regions (e.g., RWX allocations) or on classic injection patterns like `VirtualAlloc` + `WriteProcessMemory` into newly allocated memory.  
- It discusses how to select a target module, map/locate its `.text` (or other executable) section, change protections, overwrite it, and redirect execution (e.g., via a new thread or APC) while keeping the module’s metadata and presence in the PEB/module lists “legitimate-looking.”  
- The technique is positioned as an evolution/variant of process hollowing and related “stomping” approaches, emphasizing stealth tradeoffs and operational constraints (module size, relocations, CFG/ACG, integrity checks).  
- Useful for red teams and malware developers to understand modern in-memory tradecraft, and for blue teams to build detections around anomalous module code integrity and execution flow.  
- It’s interesting because it abuses trusted module context to blend payload execution into normal-looking loaded images, complicating simplistic memory-allocation-based detections.

Technical Focus:
- Windows module stomping (overwriting mapped image code sections)
- PE sections and in-memory image layout (.text, protections, relocations)
- Memory protection changes (`VirtualProtect`, RX/RWX transitions)
- Execution redirection (thread creation, APC, function pointer hijack)
- Evasion vs EDR memory-scanning heuristics (code integrity anomalies)
- Detection ideas: module code integrity validation and suspicious page modifications

Use Cases:
- Red team payload execution inside a “legitimate” loaded DLL region
- Post-exploitation tradecraft to reduce suspicious private executable memory
- Researching/demonstrating weaknesses in allocation-based injection detections
- Developing detections for modified image-backed executable pages
- Threat hunting for mismatches between on-disk module bytes and in-memory code

Keywords:
module stomping, code injection, Windows internals, DLL, PE format, .text section, image-backed memory, PEB loader lists, VirtualProtect, memory permissions, RX pages, RWX, process hollowing, APC injection, CreateRemoteThread, in-memory evasion, EDR bypass, code integrity, reflective loading, section overwrite